tebook: No surprise as Comets draw national exposure|url=https://www.chron.com/sports/barron/article/TV-Radio-Notebook-No-surprise-as-Comets-draw-2031873.php|work=Houston Chronicle|location= |access-date= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/chris-wragge/|title=Chris Wragge|last= |first= |date=February 20, 2008|website=CBS News|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref> (sideline reporter, studio host)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.nbcsports.com/nba}}\n* [http://static.espn.go.com/nba/playoffs2002/s/2002/0612/1394112.html ESPN.com \u2013 NBA \u2013 PLAYOFFS2002 \u2013 The day Tesh's music might die]\n* [http://www.mpvoice.com/mpvoice/flash/nba-low.mov nba-low.mov] [[QuickTime]] MOV video: voice-over Mitch Phillips on commercial spots for the ''NBA on NBC''.\n* [http://www.hedrickonline.com/games/showtime/ NBA Showtime: NBA on NBC]\n**[http://gr.bolt.com/games/sony/sports/nba_showtime_psx.htm NBA Showtime: NBA on NBC \u2013 Game Revolution Review Page]\n* [https://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/nba/stories/2002-01-22-tv-deal.htm NBA finalizes TV deals: Goodbye NBC]\n* [http://www.fcc.gov/Bureaus/Cable/Orders/1994/orcb4014.txt Inquiry into Sports Programming Migration]\n* [http://www.80stvthemes.com/ra/NBAONNBC.ra NBA on NBC \u2013 Short cut.]\n**[http://www.ilovewavs.com/TV/Sports/TV%20Theme%20-%20NBC,%20NBA%2002.wav TV Theme \u2013 NBC, NBA 02.wav]\n* [http://www.insidehoops.com/nba-tv-contracts.shtml InsideHoops \u2013 NBA TV Contracts]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080429142619/http://www.jumptheshark.com/topic/Nba-Nbc/Nba-Nbc-General-Comments/1412 Jump The Shark \u2013 NBA on NBC]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|before=[[NBA on DuMont|DuMont]]| title=NBA network broadcast partner| years=[[1954\u201355 NBA season|1955]] \u2013 [[1961\u201362 NBA season|1962]]| after=[[NBA on SNI|SNI]]}}\n{{succession box|before=[[NBA on CBS|CBS]]| title=NBA network broadcast partner| years=[[1990\u201391 NBA season|1990]] \u2013 [[2001\u201302 NBA season|2002]]| after=[[NBA on ABC|ABC]]}}\n{{succession box|before=League created| title=WNBA network broadcast partner| years=[[1997 WNBA season|1997]] \u2013 [[2002 WNBA season|2002]]| after=[[WNBA on ESPN|ABC]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{NBA on NBC}}\n{{NBC Sports}}\n{{National Basketball Association on television}}\n{{Sports Emmy Award for Outstanding Live Sports Series}}\n{{College Basketball on NBC}}\n{{Women's National Basketball Association on television}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nba On Nbc}}\n[[Category:Basketball on NBC]]\n[[Category:Black-and-white American television programs]]\n[[Category:CNBC original programming]]\n[[Category:National Basketball Association on television|NBC]]\n[[Category:NBC original programming]]\n[[Category:Women's National Basketball Association media|NBC]]\n[[Category:1950s American television series]]\n[[Category:1960s American television series]]\n[[Category:1990s American television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American television series]]\n[[Category:1954 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1962 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:1990 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2002 American television series endings]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the video game of the same name|NBA Showtime: NBA on NBC}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = NBA on NBC\n| image                = Nba on nbc.jpg\n| caption              = ''NBA on NBC'' logo used from [[2000\u201301 NBA season|2000]] to [[2001\u201302 NBA season|2002]]\n| show_name_2          = \n| genre                = [[National Basketball Association|NBA game telecasts]]\n| creator              = \n| director             = \n| presenter            = [[Marv Albert]]<br>[[Bob Costas]]<br>[[Ahmad Rash\u0101d]]<br>[[Hannah Storm]]<br>[[Bill Walton]]<br>[[Mike Fratello]]\n| theme_music_composer = [[John Tesh]]<ref>[https://www.facebook.com/johntesh John Tesh's Facebook page]</ref>\n| opentheme            = \"[[Roundball Rock]]\" {{small|(1991\u20132002 version)}}<ref>{{YouTube|fZKX-cf_p90|NBA on NBC Theme}}</ref>\n| endtheme             = \n| composer             = \n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| num_seasons          = 8 {{small|([[1954\u201355 NBA season|1954]]\u2013[[1961\u201362 NBA season|1962]] version)}}<br>12 {{small|([[1990\u201391 NBA season|1990]]\u2013[[2001\u201302 NBA season|2002]] version)}}<br>20 {{small|(total)}}\n| num_episodes         = \n| list_episodes        = \n| executive_producer   = \n| producer             = \n| location             = [[List of National Basketball Association arenas|Various NBA arenas]] {{small|(game telecasts)}}<br>[[NBC Studios (New York)|NBC Studios]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]] {{small|(studio segments, pre-game and post-game shows)}}\n| camera               = [[Multi-camera setup|Multi-camera]]\n| runtime              = 150 minutes or until game ends\n| company              = [[NBC Sports]]\n| distributor          = \n| network              = [[NBC]]\n| picture_format       = [[480i]] ([[Standard-definition television|SDTV]])<br>(1954-2002)<br>[[1080i]] ([[High-definition television|HDTV]])<br>(2000-2002)\n| first_aired          = {{Plainlist |\n* '''First run:''' <br> {{Start date|1954|10|30}} \u2013 {{End date|1962|4|7}}\n* '''Second run:''' <br> {{Start date|1990|11|3}} \u2013 {{End date|2002|6|12}} \n* '''[[Women's National Basketball Association|WNBA]] on NBC:''' <br> {{Start date|1997|6|21}} \u2013 {{End date|2002|8|31}}}}\n| last_aired           =  \n| preceded_by          = ''[[NBA on CBS]]''\n| followed_by          = ''[[NBA on ABC]]''\n| related              = \n| website              = http://www.nbcsports.com/nba\n| production_website   = \n}}\n\nThe '''''NBA on NBC''''' is the branding used for presentations of [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) games produced by the [[NBC]] television network in the United States. NBC held broadcast rights from [[1954\u201355 NBA season|1955]] to [[1961\u201362 NBA season|1962]] and again from [[1990\u201391 NBA season|1990]] (when it obtained the rights from [[NBA on CBS|CBS]]) to [[2001\u201302 NBA season|2002]]. During NBC's partnership with the NBA in the 1990s, the league rose to unprecedented popularity, with [[Nielsen ratings|ratings]] surpassing the days of [[Magic Johnson]] and [[Larry Bird]] in the mid-1980s.\n\n==Overview==\n===1954\u201362 incarnation===\nNBC's first tenure with the National Basketball Association<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcsports.com/our-history#decade_3|title=The NBA on NBC|last= |first= |date= |website=NBC Sports History Page|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://purl.fcla.edu/fcla/etd/amd0039|title=The NBA on Network Television: Historical Analysis|first=Mario R.|last=Sarmento}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://groups.google.com/forum/#!searchin/rec.sport.basketball.pro/NBA$20on$20NBC$20schedules%7Csort:date/rec.sport.basketball.pro/yiiWioHy9RQ/bgvxbY4wCgAJ|title=NBA on NBC regular season and playoff schedules|last= |first= |date= |website=rec.sport.basketball.pro |publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref> began on October 30, 1954 and lasted until April 7, 1962. NBC's very first NBA telecast was a game between the [[1954\u201355 Boston Celtics season|Boston Celtics]] and [[1954\u201355 Rochester Royals season|Rochester Royals]] in [[Edgerton Park Arena|Rochester]].\n\nFor the [[1954\u201355 NBA season|1954\u201355 season]], [[Marty Glickman]] and [[Lindsey Nelson]] called all games except on April 9 ([[1954\u201355 Fort Wayne Pistons season|Fort Wayne]] @ [[1954\u201355 Syracuse Nationals season|Syracuse]] during the [[1954 NBA playoffs|playoffs]]), when Glickman worked with [[Jim Gordon (sportscaster)|Jim Gordon]]. Nelson would later write in his autobiography, ''Hello Everybody, I'm Lindsey Nelson''<ref>{{cite book |last=Nelson|first=Lindsay|date= |title=Hello everybody, I'm Lindsey Nelson|url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=g_uBAAAAMAAJ&dq=Hello+Everybody%2C+I%27m+Lindsey+Nelson&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Maurice+Podoloff|location= |publisher=Beech Tree Books|page=260|isbn= |author-link=}}</ref> that [[Commissioner of the NBA|NBA commissioner]] [[Maurice Podoloff]] would travel to the televised games and, when NBC needed to get in a commercial, he would go up to one of the coaches and say, \"Call a timeout,\" and they had to, since the commissioner ordered it. On March 19, 1955 during the [[1955 NBA playoffs|playoffs]], NBC gave the national spotlight to the [[1954\u201355 New York Knicks season|New York Knicks]] and rising [[1954\u201355 Boston Celtics season|Boston Celtics]] at [[New York City|New York]]'s [[Madison Square Garden (1925)|Madison Square Garden]]. \n\nFor the first year of NBC's tenure, the first five weeks of coverage followed a [[CFL on NBC|Canadian Football League]] game. That contract decreed that the network show 13 games (along with presumably the [[1954 Grey Cup|Grey Cup]]) on Saturday afternoons beginning in late August, and was signed one week after NBC had lost the [[NBC College Football Game of the Week|rights]] to NCAA football to [[ESPN College Football on ABC|ABC]].\n\nThe [[1955\u201356 NBA season|following year]], Lindsey Nelson was paired with [[Curt Gowdy]] on commentary for all games except on February 25 ([[1955\u201356 St. Louis Hawks season|St. Louis]] @ [[1955\u201356 New York Knicks season|New York]]), March 3 ([[1955\u201356 Minneapolis Lakers season|Minneapolis]] @ [[1955\u201356 Rochester Royals season|Rochester]] with Nelson working with [[Joe Lapchick]]), and March 24 ([[1955\u201356 Fort Wayne Pistons season|Fort Wayne]] @ St. Louis with Nelson working alone). On March 31, 1956, NBC broadcast the first nationally televised [[List of NBA Finals broadcasters|NBA Finals]] game, which was Game 1 of the [[1955\u201356 Philadelphia Warriors season|Philadelphia]]-[[1955\u201356 Fort Wayne Pistons season|Fort Wayne]] [[1956 NBA Finals|series]].\n\nGowdy and Nelson were retained as the primary broadcast team for NBC in [[1956\u201357 NBA season|1956\u201357]] except on March 23 and March 30 ([[1956\u201357 St. Louis Hawks season|St. Louis]] @ [[1956\u201357 Boston Celtics season|Boston]]), when Nelson worked by himself. While the team of Gowdy and Nelson again did most games in [[1957\u201358 NBA season|1957\u201358]], Nelson worked the December 14 telecast ([[1957\u201358 Syracuse Nationals season|Syracuse]] @ [[1957\u201358 Detroit Pistons season|Detroit]]) with [[Chick Hearn]], who in return, worked the January 11 telecast (Syracuse @ [[1957\u201358 Cincinnati Royals season|Cincinnati]]) with Gowdy. For the January 18 telecast ([[1957\u201358 Detroit Pistons season|Detroit]] @ [[1957\u201358 St. Louis Hawks season|St. Louis]]), Nelson worked alone while on February 1 (Syracuse @ [[1957\u201358 Minneapolis Lakers season|Minneapolis]]), Nelson was paired with [[Bill O'Donnell (sportscaster)|Bill O'Donnell]]. Meanwhile, Gowdy worked alone on March 1 (Cincinnati @ [[1957\u201358 Philadelphia Warriors season|Philadelphia]]).\n\nNBC also during the 1957\u201358 season, broadcast a game in Detroit between Cincinnati and the Pistons on March 15. It was after this game, on the flight home to [[Cincinnati]], that [[Maurice Stokes]] became ill and later suffered a [[Epileptic seizure|seizure]], fell into a coma and was left permanently paralyzed. This was the delayed reaction from having hit his head in a game three days earlier. Stokes died in April 1970.\n\nIn the [[1958\u201359 NBA season|1958-59 season]], Curt Gowdy worked alone on all games except on March 15 ([[1958\u201359 New York Knicks season|New York]] @ [[1958\u201359 Syracuse Nationals season|Syracuse]], when Gowdy worked with [[Bud Palmer]]), April 5 ([[1958\u201359 Minneapolis Lakers season|Minneapolis]] @ [[1958\u201359 Boston Celtics season|Boston]] with Lindsey Nelson). The [[1959 NBA All-Star Game]]<ref>{{Cite news|title=NBA Coaches Add Their Choices To East-West Squad|date=January 6, 1959|newspaper=The Christian Science Monitor|page=24}}</ref> marked the first time that the [[List of NBA All-Star Game broadcasters|All-Star Game]] was nationally televised. However, NBC only broadcast the second half<ref>{{cite news|title=Sports Fans in For Big Afternoon|date=January 17, 1959|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=Daytona Beach Morning Journal|page=2B}}</ref> at 10 p.m. [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern Time]], in lieu of its ''[[Gillette Cavalcade of Sports|Friday Night Fights]]'' telecast. The fact that the All-Star Game prior to this, was almost always played on a Tuesday night meant that NBC would have had to sacrifice most, if not all, of their evening programming. In the first few years, that would have meant taking off [[Milton Berle]]'s [[Texaco Star Theatre|program]], which was starting to slide, but still would have made more money for the network than a pro basketball game. Plus, NBA owners weren't terribly savvy when it came to working with TV in this era, so they probably refused network requests to put it in a weekend afternoon slot. \n\nDuring the [[1959\u201360 NBA season|1959\u201360 season]], Curt Gowdy worked alone most on Saturday games while Lindsey Nelson worked alone on most Sunday games. Nelson also worked on Saturday April 2 ([[1959\u201360 St. Louis Hawks season|St. Louis]] @ [[1959\u201360 Boston Celtics season|Boston]]) during the [[1960 NBA playoffs|playoffs]]. Marty Glickman meanwhile, worked alone on December 6 (St. Louis @ [[1959\u201360 Cincinnati Royals season|Cincinnati]]), January 2-3 ([[1959\u201360 New York Knicks season|New York Knicks]] @ Cincinnati and Boston @ [[1959\u201360 Syracuse Nationals season|Syracuse]]), February 28 ([[1959\u201360 Philadelphia Warriors season|Philadelphia]] @ [[1959\u201360 Detroit Pistons season|Detroit]]), March 13 (Philadelphia @ Syracuse), 20 (Boston @ Philadelphia), and 27 (St. Louis @ Boston), and April 3 (Boston @ St. Louis). Finally, Bill O'Donnell worked alone on March 12 ([[1959\u201360 Minneapolis Lakers season|Minneapolis]] @ [[1959\u201360 Detroit Pistons season|Detroit]]), 19 (St. Louis @ Minneapolis), and 26 (Minneapolis @ St. Louis).\n \nIn the [[1960\u201361 NBA season|1960-61 season]], Lindsey Nelson was alone on all games except when he worked with Bud Palmer on October 22 ([[1960\u201361 New York Knicks season|New York]] @ [[1960\u201361 Cincinnati Royals season|Cincinnati]]) and 29 (New York @ [[1960\u201361 Detroit Pistons season|Detroit]]), November 26 ([[1960\u201361 Syracuse Nationals season|Syracuse]] @ [[1960\u201361 Boston Celtics season|Boston]]), December 3 (New York @ Syracuse), 10 (Syracuse @ Detroit), and 24 (Detroit @ Boston). [[Jerry Doggett]] helped call games on November 5 (Syracuse @ [[1960\u201361 Los Angeles Lakers season|Los Angeles]]) and 19 (Detroit @ Los Angeles). Marty Glickman contributed to commentary on January 8 (Boston @ [[1960\u201361 St. Louis Hawks season|St. Louis]]), 15 ([[1960\u201361 Philadelphia Warriors season|Philadelphia]] @ Syracuse), 22 (St. Louis @ Cincinnati), and 29 (Philadelphia @ Boston), February 19 (Boston @ Syracuse) and 26 (Boston @ Detroit), March 12 (Boston @ Syracuse), 19 (Syracuse @ Boston), and 26 (Syracuse @ Boston), and April 2 (St. Louis @ Boston).\n\nFor NBC's [[1961\u201362 NBA season|final season]] of their first stint with the NBA, Bud Palmer worked alone on commentary on all games except for on February 3 ([[1961\u201362 Cincinnati Royals season|Cincinnati]] @ [[1961\u201362 New York Knicks season|New York]]) and April 7 ([[1961\u201362 Los Angeles Lakers season|Los Angeles]] @ [[1961\u201362 Boston Celtics season|Boston]]), when he was paired with [[Bob Wolff]].\n\nNBC's [[Nielsen ratings|ratings]]<ref>[[#pomerantz|Pomerantz 2005]], pp.10\u201311</ref> during this time period were lukewarm at best. By 1962<ref>{{cite book |last=Pomerantz |first=Gary M. |page=[https://archive.org/details/wilt1962nightof00pome/page/80 80] |year=2005 |title=Wilt, 1962: The Night of 100 Points and the Dawn of a New Era |location=New York |publisher=Crown |isbn=1-4000-5160-6 |ref=pomerantz |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/wilt1962nightof00pome/page/80 }}</ref>, NBA ratings for NBC's Saturday afternoon games dipped to 4.8 (9 million viewers) as compared to Sunday afternoon NFL ratings of 10.4 (15 million viewers). As a matter of fact, CBS was at one point, getting better ratings<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Hockey Rebellion|url=https://www.si.com/vault/1957/10/28/605545/the-hockey-rebellion|author=Dan Parker|journal=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=October 28, 1957}}</ref> for their [[National Hockey League]] [[NHL on CBS|telecasts]] than NBC was getting with the NBA. On possible factor for the dipping ratings the fact that NBC's 1960\u201361 schedule placed the three weakest teams--[[1960\u201361 Cincinnati Royals season|Cincinnati]], [[1960\u201361 Syracuse Nationals season|Syracuse]], and [[1960\u201361 Detroit Pistons season|Detroit]] on television a total of 14 times. In comparison, three of the NBA's best teams--[[1960\u201361 Boston Celtics season|Boston]], [[1960\u201361 St. Louis Hawks season|St. Louis]], and [[1960\u201361 Philadelphia Warriors season|Philadelphia]]--appeared on NBC a total of only seven times.\n\n===1990\u201302 iteration===\n====Background====\nOn November 9, 1989, the NBA reached an agreement with the network worth US$600 million contract to broadcast the league's games for four years, beginning with the [[1990\u201391 NBA season|1990\u201391 season]]. On April 28, 1993, NBC extended its exclusive broadcast rights to the NBA with a four-year, $750 million contract.<ref>{{cite news|title=November 9, 1989: The NBA signs a lucrative 4-year television deal with NBC.|url=http://www.sportsmediawatch.com/2009/11/this-day-in-history.html|work=Sports Media Watch}}</ref>\n\n====Coverage====\nNBC's coverage of the NBA<ref>{{cite web|title=\"NBA on NBC\" Regular Season TV Schedules \u2013 1990\u20132002|url=http://the506.com/yabb/YaBB.pl?num=1231539314|work=The506.com}}</ref> began on [[Christmas|Christmas Day]] each season, with the exception of the inaugural season in 1990 (which featured a game on November 3<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcsports.com/our-history#decade_7|title=NBA on NBC introduces \"Roundball Rock\" theme song|last= |first= |date= |website=NBC Sports History Page|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref> between the [[1990\u201391 Los Angeles Lakers season|Los Angeles Lakers]] and the [[1990\u201391 San Antonio Spurs season|San Antonio Spurs]]), the [[1997\u201398 NBA season|1997\u201398 season]] (which included a [[1997 McDonald's Championship| preseason tournament]] featuring the [[1997\u201398 Chicago Bulls season|Chicago Bulls]]), the [[1998\u201399 NBA season|1998\u201399 season]] (as no Christmas games were played due to the [[1998\u201399 NBA lockout]]), and the final season of the network's contract in [[2001\u201302 NBA season|2001\u201302]] (which included two early season games featuring the return of [[Michael Jordan]] with the [[2001\u201302 Washington Wizards season|Washington Wizards]]). NBC aired the [[National Basketball Association All-Star Game|NBA All-Star Game]] every year (with the exception of [[1998\u201399 NBA season|1999]], when the game was canceled due to the lockout), usually at 6:00&nbsp;p.m., Eastern Time. In 2002, NBC aired the game an hour earlier (at 5:00&nbsp;p.m., Eastern) due to the [[2002 Winter Olympics|Winter Olympics]] later that evening. Starting in [[1999\u20132000 NBA season|2000]], during the NBA Playoffs, NBC would air tripleheaders on Saturdays and Sundays during the first two weeks of the playoffs. Prior to 2000, NBC would air a doubleheader on Saturday, followed by a tripleheader on Sunday.\n\nOn December 30, 2000, NBC aired a rare second December game. The Saturday match was the only time that NBC aired a game between Christmas Day and the start of the regular run of games in February. In [[2001\u201302 NBA season|2001]], NBC was scheduled to air an October preseason game involving an NBA team playing an international team; that game was canceled due to the [[September 11 attacks]]. During the 2001\u201302 NBA season, NBC added a significant number of Washington Wizards games to its schedule (due to the aforementioned return of Michael Jordan). When Jordan became injured during the middle of the season, the network replaced the added Wizards games with the games that had been originally on the schedule (for example, a March 2002 game between the Wizards and [[2001\u201302 Orlando Magic season|Orlando Magic]] was replaced at the last minute with an [[2001\u201302 Indiana Pacers season|Indiana Pacers]]\u2013[[2001\u201302 Sacramento Kings season|Sacramento Kings]] game).\n\n=====Music=====\n[[Image:Nba on nbc old logo.jpg|right|thumb|''NBA on NBC'' logo used from [[1990\u201391 NBA season|1990]] to [[1999\u20132000 NBA season|2000]].]]\nThe theme music for the ''NBA on NBC'' broadcasts, \"[[Roundball Rock]]\", was composed by [[New-age music|new-age]] artist [[John Tesh]]. The instrumental piece, which NBC used for every telecast during the network's twelve-year tenure. Although Tesh offered the theme to [[NBA on ABC|ABC]] when it took over the rights to the league, the network declined.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ftw.usatoday.com/2018/10/john-tesh-nba-on-nbc-roundball-rock-origin-kawhi-snl-interview|title=John Tesh on the enduring legacy of 'Roundball Rock': 'It's fun for me to watch it take on its own life'|date=2018-10-26|work=For The Win|access-date=2018-10-28|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn 1991, \"The Dream is Still Alive\" by [[Wilson Phillips]] was played during the end of the season montage. Afterwards, until [[1996 NBA Finals|1996]], NBC would play the [[rock and roll|rock song]] \"Winning It All\" by [[The Outfield]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome to THEOUTFIELD.com<!-- Bot generated title -->|url=http://www.theoutfield.com/|work=TheOutfield.com}}</ref> during its end-of-season montage. From [[1997 NBA Finals|1997]] to [[2001 NBA Finals|2001]], several contemporary music pieces were used for the montage (including, in 1997, [[R. Kelly]]'s song \"[[I Believe I Can Fly]]\", which coincidentally came from a basketball film \u2013 ''[[Space Jam]]'', which starred Michael Jordan and [[Pat Benatar]]'s song \"[[Wide Awake in Dreamland|All Fired Up]]\" from [[1999 NBA Finals|1999]] to [[2001 NBA Finals|2001]]). After the 1999 Finals, NBC used \"[[Fly Away (Lenny Kravitz song)|Fly Away]]\" by [[Lenny Kravitz]] for their montage. \n\nIn [[2002 NBA Finals|2002]], after NBC's final broadcast, the network aired a montage of memorable moments from every year of coverage, using music from \"Titans Spirit\" (from the film ''[[Remember the Titans]]'') to \"Winning It All\" and most notably, \"To The Flemish Cap\" from the 2000 film ''[[The Perfect Storm (film)|The Perfect Storm]]''. The song composed by [[James Horner]] is played at the beginning of the montage as well as the end featuring footage from the [[Los Angeles Lakers]] dynasty era. This theme song has made a brief comeback as part of NBC's Olympic basketball coverage in 2008, and again in 2016. In December 2018, [[Fox Sports]] acquired the rights to \"Roundball Rock\" for use during [[college basketball]] games.\n\n=====Segments=====\nThe pre-game show for NBC's NBA telecasts was ''[[NBA Showtime]]'', a title that was used from [[1990\u201391 NBA season|1990]] until [[2000\u201301 NBA season|2000]], with the pre-game being unbranded afterward. ''Showtime'' was originally hosted by [[Bob Costas]] from the inaugural season of the 1990 contract to the [[1995\u201396 NBA season|1995\u201396 season]]; [[Hannah Storm]] took over as host beginning with the [[1996\u201397 NBA season|1996\u201397 season]], who in turn was replaced by [[Ahmad Rash\u0101d]] in 2001 when Storm went on [[parental leave|maternity leave]]. The video game ''[[NBA Showtime NBA on NBC|NBA Showtime: NBA on NBC]]'', by [[Midway Games]], was named after the pregame show.\n\nDuring the NBA Finals, additional coverage would be immediately available on [[CNBC]], in which the panelists provided an additional half-hour of in-depth game discussions, after the NBC broadcast network's coverage concluded.\n\nThe halftime show was sponsored by [[Prudential Financial]] (''Prudential Halftime Report''), and later [[NetZero]] (''NetZero at the Half'') and [[Verizon Wireless]] (''Verizon Wireless at the Half''). The broadcasts also featured a segment during the live games called ''[[Miller Brewing|Miller]] Genuine Moments'', which provided a brief retrospective on a particular historically significant and/or dramatic moment in NBA history; this segment was discontinued towards the end of NBC's coverage. For a brief period in 2001\u201302, NBC aired a studio segment called ''24'', in which each analyst (at that time, [[Pat Croce]], [[Jayson Williams]] or Mike Fratello) would have 24 seconds to talk about issues concerning the NBA. NBC (in conjunction with completely revamping the pregame show) discontinued the segment in February 2002, after Williams was arrested on murder charges.\n\n=====Ratings=====\n{{details|topic=NBC's NBA ratings|National Basketball Association Nielsen ratings#The NBC Era 1990\u20132002}}\nDuring its twelve-year run, the ''NBA on NBC'' experienced ratings highs and lows for the NBA. In the 1990s, the NBA Finals ratings were stellar, with the exception of [[1999 NBA Finals|1999 Finals]]. In [[1998 NBA Finals|1998]], the NBA set a Finals ratings record, with an 18.7 household rating for the second [[1997\u201398 Chicago Bulls season|Chicago Bulls]]\u2013[[1997\u201398 Utah Jazz season|Utah Jazz]] series, the last championship run by the Michael Jordan-led Bulls. The very next year (after a lockout which erased part of the season), the ratings for the 1999 Finals plummeted, marking the beginning of an ongoing period of lower viewership for the league's game telecasts.<ref name=\"slump\">{{cite news|title=Basketball Ratings Hit a Slump at NBC And That Is Costly|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/03/20/business/basketball-ratings-hit-a-slump-at-nbc-and-that-is-costly.html?pagewanted=all|author=Bill Carter|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|date=March 20, 2000|accessdate=July 29, 2011}}</ref> In 2002, NBC set a record for the highest-rated [[2002 NBA Playoffs|Western Conference Final]], including a 14.2 rating for Game 7 of the series between the Los Angeles Lakers and Sacramento Kings.\n\nNBC's highest-rated regular season game was Michael Jordan's first game back from playing [[minor league baseball]]; the March [[1994\u201395 NBA season|1995]] game between the Chicago Bulls and Indiana Pacers scored a 10.9 rating (higher than all but three NBA telecasts on [[NBA on ABC|ABC]]). As a comparison, the first game in Jordan's second comeback (a game against the [[2001\u201302 New York Knicks season|New York Knicks]] that aired on [[NBA on TBS|TBS]] opposite the [[2001 World Series]]) scored a rating between a 3.0 and 4.0. NBC's first game of Jordan's second comeback scored ratings similar to that number.\n\n=====Criticisms=====\n{{details|topic=NBA on NBC accusations of bias|National Basketball Association criticisms and controversies}}\nSeveral NBA observers accused NBC and the NBA of being biased with only certain teams and individual players. NBC benefited from having [[List of NBA Finals broadcasters#1990s|all of the Finals]] it televised involve the large-market Chicago Bulls, Los Angeles Lakers, New York Knicks, [[New Jersey Nets]], [[Philadelphia 76ers]] or [[Houston Rockets]]; however, smaller-market teams such as those in San Antonio, Sacramento, [[Phoenix Suns|Phoenix]], [[Seattle SuperSonics|Seattle]], [[Portland Trail Blazers|Portland]], Utah, Indiana, Orlando and [[Miami Heat|Miami]] all made regular appearances on NBC games during its run.\n\n=====The end of ''The NBA on NBC''=====\nUpon the expiration of NBC Sports' contract with the NBA in [[2001\u201302 NBA season|2002]], the league signed a broadcast television rights agreement with [[NBA on ABC|ABC]], which began airing games in the [[2001\u201302 NBA season|2002\u201303 season]]. NBC had made a four-year, US $1.3 billion bid in the spring of 2002 to renew its NBA rights, but the league instead made six-year deals worth $4 billion with [[ESPN]], [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] and [[TNT (U.S. TV network)|TNT]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Cable Is Said to Muscle Out NBC for N.B.A. Rights|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/01/09/sports/basketball-nbc-will-live-without-nba-and-without-losses-from-it.html|author=Richard Sandomir|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|date=January 9, 2002|accessdate=July 29, 2011}}</ref> \n\nSimply put, NBC could not compete with the combined broadcast and cable<ref>{{cite news |last=Sandomir|first=Richard|date=December 15, 2001|title=PRO BASKETBALL; Cable Is Said to Muscle Out NBC for N.B.A. Rights|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/12/15/sports/pro-basketball-cable-is-said-to-muscle-out-nbc-for-nba-rights.html|work=The New York Times|location= |access-date= }}</ref> deal that [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]] had with ESPN and ABC. To put things into proper perspective, when NBC's relationship with the NBA ended in 2002, their only cable properties then were [[CNBC]] and [[MSNBC]]. The major leagues receive more money from cable<ref>{{cite news |last=Sandomir and Wise|first=Richard and Mike|date=June 12, 2002|title=PRO BASKETBALL; Final Buzzer For NBC and N.B.A.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/06/12/sports/pro-basketball-final-buzzer-for-nbc-and-nba.html|work=The New York Times|location= |access-date= }} </ref> than broadcast, due to the dual revenue stream of subscriptions and ad revenue. It took a decade for NBC to have a strong cable portfolio, which now includes [[USA Network|USA]], [[E!]], [[SyFy]], and [[NBCSN|NBC Sports Network]], among other channels. Another thing to keep in mind is the fact that NBC lost $35 million<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadspin.com/ex-nbc-sports-employee-dick-ebersol-is-the-biggest-fai-5449864|title=Ex-NBC Sports Employee: Dick Ebersol Is The Biggest Failure Of Them All|last= |first= |date=January 16, 2010|website=Deadspin|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref> because of the failure of the [[XFL (2001)|XFL]] the previous year. As [[Charles Barkley]] summed it up during halftime of Game 1 of the [[2002 NBA Finals]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=2002 NBA Finals Lakers vs Nets - Game 1|id=W8LSiDfT-g4&t}}</ref> \"If y'all hadn't wasted all that money on the XFL, y'all would still have basketball.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Journal/Issues/2013/12/09/Anniversary-Special-Issue/They-Said-It.aspx|title=Potent quotables over the years|last= |first= |date=December 9, 2013|website=Sports Business Daily|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref>\n\nWhereas NBC normally televised 33 regular games per year, ABC would generally air fewer than 20 regular season games annually. According to [[Commissioner of the NBA|NBA Commissioner]] [[David Stern]], the reduced number of network telecasts was at the league's own request since the NBA believed that they would get a higher audience for a single game (in contrast to NBC's tripleheaders). From 2002 to [[2005\u201306 NBA season|2006]], the NBA's ratings on broadcast television (ABC) dropped almost a full ratings point (from nearly a 3.0 average rating to just above a 2.0 rating). NBC averaged a 5.5 average rating during the [[2002 NBA Playoffs]]. ABC averaged a 3.3 average rating for the [[2005 NBA Playoffs]].\n\nIn response to the impending loss of NBA coverage, NBC Entertainment president [[Jeff Zucker]] said:\n\n{{cquote|We lost [[NFL on NBC|football]] two years ago, and we stayed a strong No. 1. We lost [[Major League Baseball on NBC|baseball]], and we stayed a strong No. 1. Now we're about to lose basketball, and I believe we'll stay a strong No. 1. The fact is, it's had no impact on our prime time strength. . . NBC can now program all of Sunday nights without going around basketball. I think that's a huge advantage for us. We haven't been able for the last several years to put a program at 8 o'clock (such as ''[[American Dreams]]'') because we've had the NBA.}}\n\nWithin [[2005\u201306 United States network television schedule|two years]] of the network losing the NBA rights, NBC dropped to fourth place in the prime time television rankings for the first time in its history, which was also partly the result of a weaker prime time schedule, and would more or less remain there for [[2013\u201314 United States network television schedule|almost nine years]].\n\nNBC Sports chairman [[Dick Ebersol]] said:\n\n{{cquote|The definition of winning has become distorted. If winning the rights to a property brings with it hundreds of millions of dollars in losses, what have you won? When faced with the prospect of heavy financial losses, we have consistently walked away and have done so again. ... We wish the NBA all the best. We have really enjoyed working with them for more than a decade to build the NBA brand.<ref>{{cite news|title=SportsBusinessDaily.com<!-- Bot generated title -->|url=http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=sbd.main&storyId=SBD2002012307|work=Sports Business Daily}}</ref>}}\n\nEbersol added:\n\n{{cquote|We walked away from the N.F.L., because it was the right thing to do, and we stayed No. 1 in prime-time in all the important aspects. We walked away from baseball because it was the right thing to do and we don't have to take off our fall shows to show playoff games. The N.B.A. was asking us to lose hundreds of millions of dollars.<ref>{{cite news|title=BASKETBALL; NBC Will Live Without N.B.A. and Without Losses From It|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/01/09/sports/basketball-nbc-will-live-without-nba-and-without-losses-from-it.html|work=The New York Times}}</ref>}}\n\nIn a [[Early 2000s recession|down economy]], after losing $100 million<ref>{{cite news |last=Maffei|first=John|date=December 21, 2001|title=NBC appears likely to lose NBA, too|url=https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sdut-nbc-appears-likely-to-lose-nba-too-2001dec21-story.html|work=The San Diego Union Tribune|location= |access-date= }}</ref> on the NBA in [[2000\u201301 NBA season|2000-2001]], NBC was projecting a $200-million loss in 2001-2002.<ref>{{cite news |last=Penner|first=Mike|date=December 18, 2001|title=NBC Exit Strategy Begins NBA Spin|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/dec/18/sports/sp-15805|work=Los Angeles Times|location= |access-date= }}</ref> The NBA also saw its NBC ratings<ref>{{cite news |last=Dukcevich|first=Davide|date=December 18, 2001|title=The NBA Is Blowing It |url=https://www.forbes.com/2001/12/18/1218nba.html#2bb21507343f|work=Forbes|location= |access-date= }}</ref> for the regular season fall from 4.3 in 1999 to 3.0 in 2000. Meanwhile, and the playoff ratings<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/253503-nba-on-nbc-when-basketball-was-basketball|title=NBA on NBC: When Basketball Was Basketball|last=Concon|first=Josh|date=September 12, 2009|website=Bleacher Report|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref> dipped from 6.5 to 4.9. \n\nNBC network president [[Randy Falco]] said:\n\n{{cquote|We have a responsibility to our shareholders.}}\n\nNBC's last NBA telecast to date was Game 4 of the [[2002 NBA Finals]], which closed with highlights from the network's 12-year run with the league, through the Chicago Bulls' dynasty led by Michael Jordan and [[Scottie Pippen]], the retirement of [[Larry Bird]] and [[Magic Johnson]] and the Los Angeles Lakers' new Shaq/Kobe reign. The final image of the end montage was set in an empty gym, showing a basketball bouncing into the background and ending with the message, \"Thanks for The Memories.\" Prior to the sequence, match commentators [[Marv Albert]], [[Steve Jones (basketball)|Steve Jones]] and [[Bill Walton]] evaluated the end of their NBA contract and of the series. After that, Bob Costas closed the network's last NBA broadcast with the following:\n\n{{cquote|Okay, Marv, thanks very much. And as Marv himself would say, \"it should be pointed out\" that Marv is celebrating his forty-ninth birthday tonight for a record twelfth consecutive year. Well, another season is in the books. The Lakers' title run continues with perhaps no end in sight. But as Marv said, we have reached the end of our run with the NBA. NBC's twelve years televising the league had been filled with indelible moments. And so, as we say good night, here's an appreciative look back. And for one last time, you've been watching the ''NBA on NBC''.}}<ref>{{YouTube|8KkLa4c1O24|The Final Closing Credits To The NBA on NBC}}</ref>\n\nTNT airs many of the NBA's marquee games (the [[NBA All-Star Game]], a full [[NBA Conference Finals|Conference Final]] (alternating between the Western Conference in even-numbered years and the Eastern conference in odd-numbered years), Opening Night games, and the vast majority of playoff games). In recent years, fans have reckoned it as what NBC was during that network's coverage of the league.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slamonline.com/online/2006/08/old-school-friday-3/|title=Old School Friday|date=11 August 2006|work=SLAMonline|accessdate=June 30, 2015}}</ref> TNT would seem to be the NBA's preferred carrier as well; from 2003 to 2005, TNT aired the Conference Final with the most interest from the national media ([[San Antonio Spurs|Spurs]]-[[Dallas Mavericks|Mavericks]] in [[2003 NBA Playoffs|2003]], [[Los Angeles Lakers|Lakers]]-[[Minnesota Timberwolves|Wolves]] in [[2004 NBA Playoffs|2004]] and [[Detroit Pistons|Pistons]]-[[Miami Heat|Heat]] in [[2005 NBA Playoffs|2005]]). TNT also airs most of the big games during the regular season (TNT aired a [[Shaq\u2013Kobe feud|Lakers-Heat]] game for the third straight year in [[2006-07 NBA season|2007]]), and TNT studio content is streamed to [[NBA.com]] via the ''TNT Overtime'' section.\n\nMany NBA games currently air with NBC Sports branding as part of the various [[NBC Sports Regional Networks|NBC Sports Regional Networks']] (formerly known as Comcast SportsNet) broadcast rights with individual NBA teams.\n\n=====Statistics=====\n{{NBAonNBC}}\n\n==Announcers==\n\n===1954\u20131962===\nAs previously mentioned, NBC Sports first broadcast the NBA from the [[1954\u201355 NBA season|1954\u201355]] through [[1961\u201362 NBA season|1961\u201362 seasons]]. The announcers during this period<ref>{{cite web|title=The NBA on NBC: 1954\u201355 to 1961\u201362|url=http://the506.com/yabb/YaBB.pl?num=1258875168|work=The506.com}}</ref> included:\n* [[Jerry Doggett]] (1960\u20131961)\n* [[Marty Glickman]] (1954\u20131961)\n* [[Jim Gordon (sportscaster)|Jim Gordon]] (1954\u201355)\n* [[Curt Gowdy]] (1955\u20131960)\n* [[Chick Hearn]] (1957\u20131958)\n* [[Joe Lapchick]] (1955\u201356)\n* [[Lindsey Nelson]] (1954\u20131961)\n* [[Bill O'Donnell (sportscaster)|Bill O'Donnell]] (1957\u20131960)\n* [[Bud Palmer]] (1958\u20131962)\n* [[Bob Wolff]] (1961\u20131962)\n\n===1990\u20131997===\nNBC's first broadcast team of the 1990s\u2013[[2000s (decade)|2000s]] era was made up of [[Marv Albert]] and [[Mike Fratello]], with Ahmad Rash\u0101d serving as sideline reporter. Other broadcasters at the time included [[Dick Enberg]] and [[Steve Jones (basketball)|Steve \"Snapper\" Jones]]. Aside from Rashad, [[Jim Gray (sportscaster)|Jim Gray]] and Hannah Storm also handled sideline reporting duties; before becoming the television voice of the Spurs, Lakers and [[New Orleans Pelicans|Pelicans]], [[Joel Meyers]] also started as a sideline reporter for NBC. Bob Costas presided as host of the network's pre-game show, ''NBA Showtime''.\n\nIn 1992, shortly after announcing his retirement, basketball legend Earvin \"Magic\" Johnson became a top game analyst (alongside the likes of Enberg, Albert and Fratello); however, his performance was heavily criticized.<ref>{{cite web|title=Magic's Act|url=http://static.espn.go.com/page2/s/simmons/020927.html|author=Bill Simmons|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=September 27, 2002|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021210143159/http://static.espn.go.com/page2/s/simmons/020927.html|archivedate=December 10, 2002}}</ref> Among the complaints were his apparently poor [[diction]] skills, his tendency for \"stating the obvious\", his habitual references to his playing days, and an overall lackluster chemistry with his broadcasting partners. Johnson would ultimately be slowly phased out of the ''NBA on NBC'' after helping commentate the [[1993 NBA Finals]].\n\nIn 1994, Mike Fratello left the booth (in order to become the head coach of the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]]) and was replaced with [[Matt Guokas]]. Albert and Guokas broadcast the [[1994 NBA Finals]] and were joined for the [[1995 NBA Finals]] by [[Bill Walton]]. Albert, Guokas and Walton, while not working regular season games together (Walton usually worked games with Steve Jones and play-by-play announcers [[Dick Enberg]], [[Tom Hammond]] or [[Greg Gumbel]]), broadcast the next two Finals ([[1996 NBA Finals|1996]] and [[1997 NBA Finals|1997]]) together in a three-man booth.\n\n===1998\u20132000===\n1997 was the last time Marv Albert would call the NBA Finals for NBC during the decade, as an embarrassing [[Marv Albert#Sexual assault charges|sex scandal]] forced NBC to fire Albert before the start of the [[1997\u201398 NBA season|1997\u20131998 season]]. To replace Albert, NBC tapped studio host Bob Costas for play-by-play. Matt Guokas did not return to his post as main color commentator, and was replaced by NBA legend [[Isiah Thomas]]; Costas was replaced on the pre-game show by Hannah Storm. Midway through the season, Costas and Thomas were joined by recently fired [[Detroit Pistons]] coach [[Doug Collins (basketball)|Doug Collins]]. Collins served to take some weight off Thomas, who was considered by some to be uncomfortable in the role of lead analyst. Thomas, in particular, was singled out for his soft voice and often stammered analysis.<ref>{{cite web|title=Top 10 Sports Media Busts|url=http://www.awfulannouncing.com/2012-articles/january/top-10-sports-media-busts.html|author=Ryan Yoder|work=Awful Announcing|date=January 25, 2012|accessdate=July 28, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe team of Costas, Thomas and Collins worked the major games that season including the 1998 NBA Finals (which set an all-time ratings record for the NBA). [[Mike Breen]], who played second fiddle to Albert on [[MSG (TV network)|MSG Network]]'s New York Knicks broadcasts, was hired to do select playoff games that year and was later promoted to backup announcer status. For the [[1998\u201399 NBA season|1998\u201399 season]], Thomas was moved to the studio, while Costas and Collins made up the lead team. The 1998\u20131999 season, which was marred by a lengthy [[Lockout (industry)|lockout]] (which resulted in the regular season being shortened to 50 games) included the low-rated [[1999 NBA Finals]] between the San Antonio Spurs and the New York Knicks. Albert was brought back for the [[1999\u20132000 NBA season|1999\u20132000 season]], making a return which included calling that year's lead Christmas Day game between the San Antonio Spurs and the Los Angeles Lakers from [[Staples Center]].\n\n===2000\u20132001===\nThe 2000\u20132001 season brought to an end to Bob Costas' direct role with the ''NBA on NBC'' (although Costas would work playoff games for the next two seasons and would return to host NBC's coverage for the [[2002 NBA Finals]]). Costas deferred to Marv Albert, allowing Albert to again be the lead broadcaster for the NBA, and stayed on only to deliver interviews and special features. On the studio front, Hannah Storm left her position as studio host to go on [[parental leave|maternity leave]], with Ahmad Rash\u0101d taking over for Storm; Isiah Thomas left NBC to become coach of the Indiana Pacers. Joining Ahmad Rash\u0101d were former [[Phoenix Suns]] player [[Kevin Johnson (basketball)|Kevin Johnson]] and former NBA coach [[P. J. Carlesimo]]. Marv Albert joined Doug Collins as the primary broadcast team, and the two broadcast the [[2001 NBA Finals]], which had the highest ratings for a Finals match since [[1998 NBA Finals|1998]]. After the season, Collins was hired away from NBC by the Washington Wizards, which forced the network to move the longtime secondary color duo of Steve Jones and Bill Walton to the lead broadcast team with Albert.\n\nDuring the 2001 NBA Finals between the Los Angeles Lakers and the [[Philadelphia 76ers]], NBC decided to cross-promote its NBA coverage with its then-popular quiz show ''[[The Weakest Link (U.S. game show)|The Weakest Link]]''. Two 10-minute editions of ''The Weakest Link'' aired during halftime of Games 2 and 3, featuring Bob Costas, Bill Walton and Steve Jones as contestants, along with [[Charlotte Hornets]] guard [[Baron Davis]] and [[WNBA]] team [[Los Angeles Sparks]]'s center, [[Lisa Leslie]].\n\n===2001\u20132002===\nThe [[2001\u201302 NBA season|2001\u20132002]] season featured several anomalies, as NBC started their coverage on the first Saturday of the season, for the first time since 1991. The reason for this was NBA legend Michael Jordan's return to playing, this time for the Washington Wizards. NBC covered an early December game featuring Jordan's Wizards as well, which marked the first time a broadcast television network aired more than one pre-Christmas NBA game since [[NBA on CBS|CBS]] in the 1980s.\n\nThat year also marked the return of Hannah Storm from maternity leave, with her and Ahmad Rash\u0101d alternating as studio hosts throughout the [[2001\u201302 NBA season|2002]] season. That year, NBC's studio team consisted of Rashad and Storm with former Philadelphia 76ers owner Pat Croce, the returning Mike Fratello, and former player Jayson Williams. The tandem stayed together through the [[2002 NBA All-Star Game]]. During the week between the All-Star Game and NBC's next scheduled telecast, Williams was arrested after shooting and killing his limousine driver. He was promptly fired by NBC, which also did not return Croce or Fratello to studio coverage. Instead, the network brought in [[Tom Tolbert]], who had only recently been added to NBC Sports as a third-string analyst paired with Mike Breen. Tolbert stayed on as the lone studio analyst through the end of the season, and won acclaim by several in the media, including ''[[USA Today]]'' sports columnist Rudy Martzke. Hannah Storm was not able to anchor the [[2002 NBA All-Star Game]] as she was on assignment at the [[2002 Winter Olympics]] in [[Salt Lake City]] serving as daytime studio host; Rash\u0101d solo anchored from the studio.\n\nIn June 2002, Ahmad Rash\u0101d told the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', in an interview conducted before the [[2002 NBA Finals]] began, that he would be ending his 20-year run with NBC Sports, after hosting the pre-game show for Game 3 of the Finals.<ref>{{cite news|title=Walton Delivers the Jabs, O'Neal the Knockout|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2002-jun-10-sp-tvcolumn10-story.html|author=Larry Stewart|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|publisher=Times Mirror Company|date=June 10, 2002|accessdate=May 19, 2011}}</ref> Hannah Storm, meanwhile, covered the 2002 NBA Finals as host of the CNBC post-game show.\n\nTwo days before NBC was to begin its playoff coverage, both Marv Albert and Mike Fratello, returning from working a Philadelphia 76ers\u2013Indiana Pacers game on [[NBA on TNT|TNT]], were seriously injured in a limousine accident. That week, NBC juggled its announcing teams, which resulted in Bob Costas and [[Paul Sunderland]] working some early-round playoff games. Fratello would return to TNT after several days, and Albert returned to NBC for Game 1 of the Western Conference Semifinals between the [[Dallas Mavericks]] and Sacramento Kings.\n\nThe season would also turn out to be [[NBA on ABC#Backstory|NBC's last with the NBA]]. In January 2002, the league announced a six-year agreement with [[The Walt Disney Company]] and [[WarnerMedia|AOL Time Warner]], which resulted in the broadcast television rights being acquired by ABC. That year, NBC's playoff ratings were much higher than in previous years, including tallying record-high ratings for the [[NBA Conference Finals#Conference Finals 2|2002 Western Conference Finals]]. Those high ratings did not translate to the [[2002 NBA Finals|Finals]], which scored their lowest ratings in over two decades.\n\n===List of broadcasters===\n* [[Marv Albert]] \u2013 lead play-by-play (1990\u20131997 and 2001\u20132002)\n* [[Mike Breen]] \u2013 play-by-play\n* [[Quinn Buckner]] \u2013 studio analyst\n* [[P. J. Carlesimo]] \u2013 studio analyst, game analyst\n* [[Doug Collins (basketball)|Doug Collins]] \u2013 game analyst (1998\u20132001)\n* [[Bob Costas]] \u2013 studio host (1990\u20131997) and lead play-by-play (1998\u20132000)\n* [[Don Criqui]] \u2013 play-by-play\n* [[Pat Croce]] \u2013 studio analyst\n* [[Chuck Daly]] \u2013 game analyst\n* [[Dick Enberg]] \u2013 play-by-play\n* [[Julius Erving]] \u2013 studio analyst\n* [[Cotton Fitzsimmons]] \u2013 game analyst\n* [[Mike Fratello]] \u2013 game analyst (1990\u20131993), studio analyst (2001\u20132002)\n* [[Jim Gray (sportscaster)|Jim Gray]] \u2013 sideline reporter\n* [[Greg Gumbel]] \u2013 play-by-play (1994\u20131998; left in January to return to [[CBS Sports]])\n* [[Matt Guokas]] \u2013 game analyst\n* [[Tom Hammond]] \u2013 play-by-play\n* [[Dan Hicks (sportscaster)|Dan Hicks]] \u2013 play-by-play\n* [[Dan Issel]] \u2013 game analyst\n* [[Kevin Johnson (basketball)|Kevin Johnson]] \u2013 studio analyst\n* [[Lewis Johnson]] \u2013 sideline reporter\n* [[Magic Johnson]] \u2013 game analyst\n* [[Steve Jones (basketball)|Steve \"Snapper\" Jones]] \u2013 game analyst\n* [[Andrea Joyce]] \u2013 sideline reporter\n* [[Jim Lampley]] \u2013 play-by-play\n* [[Lisa Malosky]] \u2013 sideline reporter\n* [[Joel Meyers]] \u2013 sideline reporter\n* [[Bob Neal (Atlanta sportscaster)|Bob Neal]] \u2013 play-by-play\n* [[Ahmad Rash\u0101d]] \u2013 sideline reporter, studio host\n* [[Pat Riley]] \u2013 studio analyst\n* [[Ron Rothstein]] \u2013 game analyst\n* [[John Salley]] \u2013 studio analyst\n* [[Hannah Storm]] \u2013 sideline reporter, studio host\n* [[Paul Sunderland]] \u2013 play-by-play\n* [[Isiah Thomas]] \u2013 game analyst (1997\u20131998), studio analyst (1998\u20132000)\n* [[Tom Tolbert]] \u2013 game analyst, studio analyst\n* [[Peter Vecsey (sports columnist)|Peter Vecsey]] \u2013 studio analyst\n* [[Bill Walton]] \u2013 studio analyst, game analyst\n* [[Jayson Williams]] \u2013 studio analyst\n\n===Voice-over artists===\nJim Fagan's voice was heard in nearly every single NBA telecast on NBC; as the voice behind \"This is the NBA on NBC\", he also did several voice-over promotions for the network's game broadcasts, along with \"arena announcer\" duties in [[EA Sports]]'s ''[[NBA Live (video game series)|NBA Live]]'' video game series. Mitch Phillips also did voice-over work for the broadcasts, primarily for [[promo (media)|promotions]].<ref>{{YouTube|u4FBnkdq9KI|NBA NBC 1993 Promo}}</ref>\n\n==''WNBA on NBC''==\n{{Infobox television\n| italic_title         = \n| show_name            = ''WNBA on NBC''\n| image                = [[Image:TheWNBAonNBC.jpg|frameless]]\n| image_upright        = \n| image_size           = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = \n| alt_name             = \n| native_name          = \n| genre                = [[Women's National Basketball Association|WNBA basketball telecasts]]\n| creator              = \n| based_on             = \n| developer            = \n| writer               = \n| screenplay           = \n| story                = \n| director             = \n| creative_director    = \n| presenter            = \n| starring             = [[Bruce Beck]]<br>[[Mike Breen]]<br>[[Tom Hammond]]<br>[[Dan Hicks (sportscaster)|Dan Hicks]]<br>[[Marion Jones]]<br>[[Andrea Joyce]]<br>[[Ann Meyers]]<br>[[Lisa Malosky]]<br>[[Ahmad Rash\u0101d]]<br>[[Summer Sanders]]<br>[[Hannah Storm]]<br>[[Paul Sunderland]]<br>[[Chris Wragge]]\n| judges               = \n| voices               = \n| narrated             = \n| theme_music_composer = [[John Tesh]]\n| opentheme            = \"[[Roundball Rock]]\"\n| endtheme             = \n| composer             = \n| country              = \n| language             = \n| num_seasons          = 6\n| num_episodes         = \n| list_episodes        = \n| executive_producer   = [[Dick Ebersol]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Kent|first=Milton|date=June 28, 1996|title=Deal to televise Women's NBA shows NBC as bold yet pragmatic|url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/bs-xpm-1996-06-28-1996180021-story.html|work=The Baltimore Sun|location= |access-date= }}</ref>\n| producer             = \n| news_editor          = \n| location             = \n| cinematography       = \n| animator             = \n| editor               = \n| camera               = Multi-camera \n| runtime              = 120 minutes+ \n| company              = [[NBC Sports]]\n| distributor          = \n| budget               = \n| network              = \n| picture_format       = [[480i]] ([[SDTV]]) (1997-1999)<br>[[1080i]] ([[High-definition television|HDTV]]) (2000-2002)\n| audio_format         = \n| first_run            = \n| released             = \n| first_aired          = {{Start date|1997|06|21}} \n| last_aired           = {{End date|2002|08|31}} \n| preceded_by          = \n| followed_by          = \n| related              = ''NBA on NBC''\n| website              = https://www.nbcsports.com/wnba\n| production_website   = \n}}\n\n[[NBC]] showed [[Women's National Basketball Association]] games from [[1997 WNBA season|1997]] to [[2002 WNBA season|2002]] as part of their ''NBA on NBC''<ref>\n{{cite book |last=Swayne, Dodds|first=Linda E., Mark|author-link= |date= |title=Encyclopedia of Sports Management and Marketing|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gDp1AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA1662&lpg=PA1662&dq=WNBA+on+NBC+2002&source=bl&ots=efKBw4zfCL&sig=ACfU3U1KY1nnj-_sTQrkaC7MsSG4HD6_vQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiz7-aM4oDpAhXnmq0KHbnqD9E4ChDoATAIegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=WNBA%20on%20NBC%202002&f=false|location= |publisher=SAGE Publications|page=1662|isbn=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://la84.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/tv2000.pdf|title=Gender in Televised Sports: 1989, 1993 and 1999|last= |first= |date= |website=la84.org|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref> coverage before the league transferred the rights<ref>{{cite news |last=Penner|first=Mike|date=December 18, 2001|title=NBC Exit Strategy Begins NBA Spin|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2001-dec-18-sp-15805-story.html|work=Los Angeles Times|location= |access-date= }}</ref> to [[WNBA on ESPN|ABC/ESPN]]<ref>{{cite book |last= Miller, Shales|first=James Andrew, Tom|author-link= |date= |title=Those Guys Have All the Fun: Inside the World of ESPN|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SkYN5eMreOUC&pg=PT352&lpg=PT352&dq=WNBA+on+NBC+dick+ebersol&source=bl&ots=61OcvAOYid&sig=ACfU3U3m5JaC3oFyYyKm3RvJsMoRg7mcAg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjNs6fu8IDpAhUFXa0KHervAlc4ChDoATABegQICBAB#v=onepage&q=WNBA%20on%20NBC%20dick%20ebersol&f=false|location= |publisher=Little, Brown|page= |isbn=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Reynolds|first=Mike|date=June 16, 2002|title=ESPN's Come a Long Way, WNBA|url=https://www.multichannel.com/news/espns-come-long-way-wnba-153211|work=Multichannel News|location= |access-date= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=June 5, 2002|title=Stern Talks Smack With Rome: TV Deal And WNBA Profitability|url=https://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Issues/2002/06/05/Leagues-Governing-Bodies/Stern-Talks-Smack-With-Rome-TV-Deal-And-WNBA-Profitability.aspx|work=Sports Business Daily|location= |access-date= }}</ref>. A more [[Rock music|rock]]-oriented variant<ref>{{YouTube|title=The WNBA on NBC Theme Song|id=WkWaxH1r8Pk}}</ref> of [[John Tesh]]'s theme, \"[[Roundball Rock]]\" introduced by NBC to coincide with the debut of the WNBA. \n\n===Background===\nOn June 27, 1996, NBC Sports was announced as the WNBA's first national broadcaster<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wnba.com/archive/wnba/history/makingthewnba_timeline.html|title=The Formation of the WNBA|last=Araton|first=Harvey|date=May 13, 2016|website=WNBA.com|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref>. The WNBA soon, also had television deals in place with the [[Walt Disney Company]] and [[Hearst Corporation]] joint venture channels, [[ESPN]] and [[Lifetime Television]] Network, respectively. At the time, NBC didn't pay television rights fees<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.womenshistory.org/articles/we-got-next|title=\"We Got Next!\"|last= |first= |date=October 1, 2018|website=National Women's History Museum|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= |title=Salary Doesn\u2019t Pay in WNBA|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2000-may-29-sp-35297-story.html|work=Los Angeles Time|location= |access-date= }}</ref> to the league's teams.\n\nNBC<ref>{{cite news |last=Gustkey|first=Earl|date=May 29, 2000|title=As W.N.B.A. Opens Its 20th Season, Key Figures Recall the First Game|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/05/14/sports/basketball/wnba-opens-its-20th-season-recall-los-angeles-sparks.html|work=The New York Times|location= |access-date= }}<</ref> nationally televised the very first<ref>{{cite news |last=Voepel|first=Mechelle |date=June 16, 2016|title=Twenty seasons later, a look back at the WNBA's first game|url=https://www.espn.com/wnba/story/_/id/16256278/twenty-years-later-look-back-wnba-first-game|work=ESPN|location= |access-date= }}</ref> WNBA game on June 21, 1997. The game featured the [[1997 New York Liberty season|New York Liberty]] facing the [[1997 Los Angeles Sparks season|Los Angeles Sparks]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Lopez|first=Steve|date=June 30, 1997|title=THEY GOT NEXT TIPPING OFF TO LARGE CROWDS AND GREAT EXPECTATIONS, THE HYPER-HYPED WNBA FELL SHORT ONLY ON THE COURT|url=https://vault.si.com/vault/1997/06/30/they-got-next-tipping-off-to-large-crowds-and-great-expectations-the-hyper-hyped-wnba-fell-short-only-on-the-court|work=Sports Illustrated|location= |access-date= }}</ref> in [[Los Angeles]]. For NBC's final season with the WNBA in 2002<ref>{{cite news |last=Robbins|first=Lenn|date=May 24, 2002|title=LIBERTY TIP OFF THEIR SEASON ON LONG, WINDING ROAD|url=https://nypost.com/2002/05/24/liberty-tip-off-their-season-on-long-winding-road/|work=New York Post|location= |access-date= }}</ref>, they again began their season's worth of coverage on [[Memorial Day]] weekend<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=April 26, 2002 |title=Three Former Longhorn Basketball Players Assigned to WNBA Teams|url=https://big12sports.com/news/2002/4/26/1517141.aspx|work=Big 12 Sports|location= |access-date= }}</ref> with the [[2002 New York Liberty season|Liberty]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Howell|first=John|date=March 29, 2002|title=LIEBERMAN SEES A WNBA TOWN|url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-xpm-2002-03-29-0203292016-story.html|work=Hartford Courant|location= |access-date= }}</ref> and [[2002 Los Angeles Sparks season|Sparks]]<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=February 1, 2002|title=Starzz release schedule|url=https://www.deseret.com/2002/2/1/19634665/starzz-release-schedule|work= Deseret News|location= |access-date= }}</ref>. NBC would proceed to televise WNBA games on Saturday<ref>{{cite news |last=Johnson|first=L.C.|date=July 23, 2001|title=HARRISON IS NOT THE ONLY WNBA BEAUTY|url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/os-xpm-2001-07-23-0107230233-story.html|work=The Orlando Sentinel|location= |access-date= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Robb|first=Sharon|date=June 18, 1998|title=A LEAGUE OF THEIR OWN|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-xpm-1998-06-10-9806090379-story.html|work=South Florida Sun-Sentinel|location= |access-date= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Levin|first=Gary|date=June 27, 1997|title=WNBA scores big in ratings|url=https://variety.com/1997/scene/vpage/wnba-scores-big-in-ratings-1117342836/|work=Variety|location= |access-date= }}</ref> and Sunday<ref>{{YouTube|title=WNBA on NBC Promos / 1998 & 2001|id=DFpIX_-lyeI}}</ref> afternoons culminating in the [[1997 WNBA Championship|Championship game]] on August 30<ref>{{cite news |last=Burris|first=Joe|date=June 19, 1997|title=Lobo center of WNBA's attention|url=http://archive.boston.com/globe/packages/year_in_review/sports/wnba.htm|work=Boston Globe|location= |access-date= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Gustkey|first=Earl|date=June 18, 1997|title=Ball Is in Their Court : WNBA Takes Its Turn on Basketball Stage Starting Saturday|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1997-06-18-sp-4417-story.html|work=Los Angeles Times|location= |access-date= }}</ref>.\n\nNBC's halftime report was sponsored by [[Lee (jeans)|Lee Jeans]].\n\n====Ratings====\nNBC Sports' broadcast of the inaugural WNBA game between the Liberty and Sparks received a 3.8 overnight national rating<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=June 23, 1997|title=NOW WHO WOULD'VE GUESSED THIS? WNBA TIP-OFF GETS 3.8 RATING|url=https://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Issues/1997/06/23/Sports-Media/NOW-WHO-WOULDVE-GUESSED-THIS-WNBA-TIP-OFF-GETS-38-RATING.aspx|work=Sports Business Daily|location= |access-date= }}</ref>. Although the NBC's end-of-season average<ref>{{cite news |last=Lopiano|first=Dean|date=December 13, 1999|title=WNBA\u2019s remarkable 1999 blows the vultures out of the sky|url=https://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Journal/Issues/1999/12/13/No-Topic-Name/Wnba146s-Remarkable-1999-Blows-The-Vultures-Out-Of-The-Sky.aspx|work=Sports Business Daily|location= |access-date= }}</ref> for [[1999 WNBA season|1999]] was even with [[1998 WNBA season|1998]]'s average, viewership had actually increased from 1,540,000 households in 1998<ref>{{cite news |last=Shaprio|first=Leonard|date=June 18, 1998|title=WNBA Has All the Angles Covered|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/mystics/longterm/preview98/articles/waves.htm|work=Washington Post|location= |access-date= }}</ref> to 1,607,000 in 1999. On the same token however, Nielsen ratings for NBC broadcasts of WNBA games slipped<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=November 29, 1999|title=A Dud of Their Own|url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/1999/1129/6413080a.html#350345d1788b|work=Forbes|location= |access-date= }}</ref> from 2 million households reached in 1997--the WNBA's inaugural season--to 1.5 million in 1999<ref>{{cite news |last= Petrecca|first=Laura|date=October 9, 2000|title=HOW MUCH IS TOO MUCH?|url=https://adage.com/article/news//56669|work=Ad Age|location= |access-date= }}</ref>.\n\nThe average [[Nielsen ratings|rating]] for the first 9 of the 10<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=January 16, 1998|title=PLUS: BASKETBALL; W.N.B.A. Releases 1998 Schedule ...|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/01/16/sports/plus-basketball-wnba-releases-1998-schedule.html|work=The New York Times|location= |access-date= }}</ref> WNBA games NBC carried in the [[2001 WNBA season|2001 season]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Isidore|first=Chris|date=August 17, 2001|title=WNBA: lovable money loser|url=https://money.cnn.com/2001/08/17/companies/column_sportsbiz/|work=CNN Money|location= |access-date= }}</ref> was only 1.1, compared to a 2.0 rating its first season<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=August 12, 1997|title=Catching On If Nothing Else, Wnba Is A Hit With Its TV Exposure|url=https://www.spokesman.com/stories/1997/aug/12/catching-on-if-nothing-else-wnba-is-a-hit-with/|work=The Spokesman-Review|location= |access-date= }}</ref>.\n\n===Announcers===\n{{see also|List of WNBA Finals broadcasters}}\n\n* [[Bruce Beck]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/on-air/about-us/bruce_beck/1845253/|title=Bruce Beck|last= |first= |date=October 21, 2008|website=NBC New York|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref> (sideline reporter)\n*[[Mike Breen]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://brandonsteiner.com/blogs/unplugged/episode-124-mike-breen|title=Episode #124: Mike Breen|last= |first= |date=July 24, 2018|website=Brandon Steiner|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Sandomir|first=Richard|date=June 5, 2016|title=Mike Breen Becomes N.B.A. Finals Play-by-Play Fixture|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/06/sports/basketball/mike-breen-becomes-nba-finals-play-by-play-fixture.html|work=The New York Times|location= |access-date= }}</ref> (play-by-play)\n* [[Tom Hammond]] (play-by-play)\n* [[Dan Hicks (sportscaster)|Dan Hicks]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Brown, O'Rourke|first=Robert S., Daniel J.|author-link= |date= |title=Case Studies in Sport Communication|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7TqZvCphyDIC&pg=PA30&lpg=PA30&dq=WNBA+dan+hicks&source=bl&ots=xSQEBirl10&sig=ACfU3U0usSfl54z21fqg6IJn1mlbFuC52g&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjSj4H25YDpAhVIX60KHVsiChoQ6AEwC3oECAsQAQ#v=onepage&q=WNBA%20dan%20hicks&f=false|location= |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|page=30|isbn=}}</ref> (studio host)\n* [[Marion Jones]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Schlosser|first=Joe|date=June 6, 2001|title=Marion Jones on NBC's WNBA team|url=https://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/marion-jones-nbcs-wnba-team-88600|work=Broadcasting & Cable|location= |access-date= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Johnson|first=L.C.|date=June 8, 2001|title=DAVIS' DOUBLE DUTY DRAWS BIGGER PROFILE|url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/os-xpm-2001-06-08-0106080258-story.html|work=Orlando Sentinel|location= |access-date= }}</ref> (sideline reporter)\n* [[Andrea Joyce]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nbcsportsgrouppressbox.com/bio/andrea-joyce/|title=ANDREA JOYCE|last= |first= |date= |